I got busy, but I wanted to say, thanks for all your responses to my hard sci-fi question, Anons. Also, that was a solid synthwave compilation, really got me hooked and rocking my shoulders at the 8-minute mark.

>>33097722
>>33098965
I'm a bit lost here, the writing's not bad. It's very... r/hfy/, which lends a certain cringe handicap to it by default (first paragraph fellating affectations of the human condition, for one), but the writing itself is good. The story fails to make me very interested in Davenport, but I'm charmed by his mechanical companion. The author does a pretty 80/100 job of showing over telling, too, which is very good; he engages my mind's eye well enough to establish a sense of place within my imagination. Pacing isn't fantastic, but not bad; using amnesia and in medias res as devices to skip potentially boringb opening sections is something I'm admittedly guilty of. Our Reddiauthor seems to struggle with tense consistency, and whoever was marking up his story sucks at correcting it appreciably. I'm sensing some-- perhaps unfairly--front-loaded disdain for the story stemming from where it's from; I'd like to know what your thoughts are, though. There are genuinely horrid and eye-gouging efforts at writing on that sub, but this one's really not terrible at all, just dry.

TL:DR they're not as nice looking but you can do more with smaller overworld sprites
